1
00:00:00,638 --> 00:00:27,995
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:28,550 --> 00:00:37,643
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:37,722 --> 00:00:48,978
Today I just wanted to take the opportunity to just go over what we did, just so that you get the overall picture of what we did these past, what we've been doing these past 10 weeks, 11 weeks.

4
00:00:54,106 --> 00:00:56,770
Because it comes to the end of my session.

5
00:00:57,290 --> 00:00:58,152
Next week it's

6
00:00:58,402 --> 00:01:26,450
snoring with a bit of luck so we were really looking at the human condition and the thing we have to I think remember is that the Buddha doesn't pull any punches so he wants us really to face reality directly and he does this in the first what we call the first discourse

7
00:01:26,734 --> 00:01:28,177
Turning of the wheel of the law.

8
00:01:28,757 --> 00:01:31,460
Now that isn't exactly what he said obviously.

9
00:01:31,501 --> 00:01:34,384
But it's sort of the platform of his whole teaching.

10
00:01:35,045 --> 00:01:38,849
And it begins with this word dukkha.

11
00:01:39,090 --> 00:01:41,233
There is dukkha.

12
00:01:41,533 --> 00:01:42,974
And dukkha just means hard to bear.

13
00:01:43,394 --> 00:01:45,938
We translate it as suffering.

14
00:01:45,957 --> 00:01:48,522
But it's also translated as unsatisfactoriness.

15
00:01:49,483 --> 00:01:51,125
So it's the whole gamut really.

16
00:01:51,284 --> 00:01:53,528
Of the whole problem of human living.

17
00:01:54,489 --> 00:01:55,510
And he centres us.

18
00:01:55,878 --> 00:02:00,504
begins to center us specifically on the suffering that we can't do anything about.

19
00:02:01,064 --> 00:02:02,085
And that's where we started.

20
00:02:02,105 --> 00:02:06,010
We started with sickness, old age, or aging and death.

21
00:02:06,871 --> 00:02:21,852
And if you remember, we had, he first of all, you know, points out to King Pasenadi of Kosala that it doesn't matter what station of life you are, rich or famous, whatever, sickness, old age and death is going to come.

22
00:02:22,388 --> 00:02:28,456
And he has the image of the mountains, the three great mountains, stalking on poor Bindi Sara.

23
00:02:29,177 --> 00:02:30,681
So he's full of good cheer.

24
00:02:30,920 --> 00:02:33,944
And then there's the divine messengers.

25
00:02:34,205 --> 00:02:51,551
So this goes back to the myth that surrounds his own awakening, where sometime in his early 20s, probably, something like that, the idea of six old age and death comes to him very much so as a sort of an existential problem.

26
00:02:52,223 --> 00:02:54,486
And it drives him to seek an answer.

27
00:02:56,469 --> 00:03:11,473
And it's put in that mythological sense of, you know, he's out hunting and he sees a very sick person, a very old person, and a corpse, and this person sitting under a tree, a samana sitting under a tree.

28
00:03:11,492 --> 00:03:14,157
So they're known as the divine messengers, right?

29
00:03:14,177 --> 00:03:17,622
But basically they are little awakenings.

30
00:03:18,699 --> 00:03:30,621
And if you remember, there's this lovely little parable about this man who's born in hell with Yama.

31
00:03:30,961 --> 00:03:41,741
And Yama keeps asking him, you know, didn't you ever see my good man, the first divine messenger appearing among humankind?

32
00:03:42,222 --> 00:03:43,002
I did not see him.

33
00:03:43,826 --> 00:04:02,835
By good man, did you never see a woman or a man, 80, 90 or 100 years old, frail, bent like a roof bracket, crooked, leaning on a stick, shakily going along, ailing, youth and vigor gone, with broken teeth, with grey and scanty hair or bald, wrinkled with blotched limbs.

34
00:04:03,455 --> 00:04:04,257
I mean...

35
00:04:06,360 --> 00:04:09,403
So he saw her and he says, no, I haven't seen her.

36
00:04:09,424 --> 00:04:09,884
He says, well,

37
00:04:10,320 --> 00:04:17,173
It didn't ever occur to you, an intelligent and mature person, that I too am subject to old age, cannot escape it.

38
00:04:19,156 --> 00:04:27,971
So there's a lovely parable about Yama, King Yama, who's in charge of hell, the hell realms.

39
00:04:27,992 --> 00:04:32,358
Remember that hell in Buddhism is not permanent.

40
00:04:32,379 --> 00:04:35,805
It's still horrible, but it's not permanent.

41
00:04:36,257 --> 00:04:42,206
So those, he's pointing to the fact that there are things in our lives which are just part and parcel of the human condition.

42
00:04:42,927 --> 00:04:48,735
And that we can't do anything about that except form a right relationship with it.

43
00:04:48,755 --> 00:04:52,442
And that's when he talks about patience and forbearance.

44
00:04:53,023 --> 00:04:59,031
See, that's when he talks to, I think it was King Bin Bisara, doesn't he?

45
00:04:59,052 --> 00:04:59,952
Somewhere along the line.

46
00:05:08,793 --> 00:05:28,391
See, remember, the king says to him, I've been engaged in these affairs of kingship, typical for kings, who are intoxicated with the intoxication of sovereignty, who are obsessed by greed of sensual pleasures, and who have attained stable control in their country, and who rule having conquered a great sphere of territory on earth, you see.

47
00:05:29,692 --> 00:05:35,137
And then he says, but this great peril, this terrible thing, the destruction of human life,

48
00:05:35,692 --> 00:05:39,057
the human state being so difficult to obtain, etc., etc.

49
00:05:40,019 --> 00:05:43,144
And then he advises him, you see, to get his act straight.

50
00:05:46,930 --> 00:05:54,543
As aging and death are rolling in on you, what else should you do but to live by the Dharma, live righteously and do wholesome and meritorious deeds?

51
00:05:55,064 --> 00:05:59,535
So it's a case of acceptance that there's no escape from these things in life.

52
00:05:59,555 --> 00:06:06,151
So what's really going to undermine our suffering around that area is getting the right relationship to it.

53
00:06:06,170 --> 00:06:10,802
So the acceptance, the patience, the forbearance.

54
00:06:10,822 --> 00:06:11,925
Then the next section...

55
00:06:12,091 --> 00:06:14,572
was the suffering that we don't have to suffer.

56
00:06:14,834 --> 00:06:17,755
So this is, in a sense, more important.

57
00:06:17,776 --> 00:06:20,899
And if you remember, we had the image of the two darts.

58
00:06:21,420 --> 00:06:26,584
So it's bad enough being ill, but getting depressed about being ill is unnecessary.

59
00:06:26,985 --> 00:06:28,627
Full stop, you see.

60
00:06:29,487 --> 00:06:30,608
So it's an option.

61
00:06:30,889 --> 00:06:39,836
We have an option not to feel depressed when we get ill. And then he goes on about uninstructed worldly desires.

62
00:06:39,985 --> 00:07:09,334
worldlings and those who are uninstructed and those who are uninstructed experiences a painful feeling so then he sorrows, grieves, laments she weeps beating her breast becomes distraught they have two feelings a bodily one and a mental one so he's pointing to the fact that that isn't necessary and it's the same with then we discuss the eight vicissitudes of life vicissitudes of life

63
00:07:10,732 --> 00:07:15,761
There's gain and loss, fame and disrepute, praise and blame, pleasure and pain.

64
00:07:16,521 --> 00:07:17,504
How to be above that?

65
00:07:18,165 --> 00:07:21,490
Sometimes life works for us and we're doing okay, sometimes we lose it.

66
00:07:22,031 --> 00:07:24,475
Sometimes people love us and sometimes people don't.

67
00:07:26,579 --> 00:07:30,125
Sometimes people think we're absolutely fantastic, sometimes people think we're horrible.

68
00:07:30,146 --> 00:07:31,588
Praise and blame is your fault.

69
00:07:32,790 --> 00:07:34,072
And then there's pleasure and pain.

70
00:07:34,322 --> 00:07:41,728
And again, it's this business of being able to deal with these vicissitudes of life so that they don't actually get into us.

71
00:07:41,749 --> 00:07:47,473
So, you know, as today, you know, people are losing work and whatnot, so that's bad enough, see?

72
00:07:47,494 --> 00:07:53,738
But to actually find ourselves getting depressed about it, anxious about it, see?

73
00:07:53,759 --> 00:07:56,901
Unnecessary.

74
00:07:56,922 --> 00:08:00,704
And if you remember, when fame comes, he feels elated.

75
00:08:01,086 --> 00:08:03,908
When he meets with disrepute, he feels dejected, see?

76
00:08:06,351 --> 00:08:34,148
all good stuff and then we had this whole thing about anxiety and that this anxiety about change so remember the self so we went into all the business of the self and how we regard ourselves how we perceive ourselves as being some individual complete individual in a sense

77
00:08:34,380 --> 00:09:02,937
kidding ourselves that we're in charge that we have this control that we don't have and there were different ways in which we see ourselves either as the body and mind or inside it or that we're possessed within the body and mind and so on and so forth but it's this business of we always want to stop the world as soon as we've got something good we just want to hold it there, don't move just keep it going and the fact of

78
00:09:03,270 --> 00:09:05,274
That everything is impermanent, you see.

79
00:09:05,553 --> 00:09:07,096
Therefore we can't control it.

80
00:09:08,297 --> 00:09:09,818
Therefore nothing is reliable.

81
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:13,003
So this is the cause of our anxiety.

82
00:09:14,065 --> 00:09:22,575
And remember that for the most part, what we're anxious about never actually happens.

83
00:09:23,496 --> 00:09:27,280
Because it's the mind's business to try and visualize the future, you see.

84
00:09:27,902 --> 00:09:30,966
So the mind's always throwing it forward, even when we're ill.

85
00:09:31,333 --> 00:09:56,581
if we have a painful say illness actually what's happening in the present for most people for most illnesses is some discomfort of some at some level and some inability like you can't go out or you can't do this or you can't do that but then the mind launches it into days and months and years of the same problem and then of course you feel horrible or depressed and terrible

86
00:10:01,101 --> 00:10:09,674
And then, once we discussed how we cause suffering for ourselves, which is unnecessary, we then talked about the world.

87
00:10:10,054 --> 00:10:11,538
See, what happens in the world?

88
00:10:11,998 --> 00:10:15,724
Why is it, the question is, that people end up fighting?

89
00:10:16,745 --> 00:10:26,019
See, I mean, in those days, the warrior caste fought the warrior caste, and the priestly caste, the Brahmins fought the priestly caste, and householders, householders, see?

90
00:10:27,081 --> 00:10:29,725
And the first thing we discussed

91
00:10:29,941 --> 00:10:32,868
discussed was this attachment to views and opinions.

92
00:10:33,469 --> 00:10:35,092
Obsessed with views and opinions.

93
00:10:35,113 --> 00:10:36,254
See?

94
00:10:36,274 --> 00:10:39,923
So you've only got to think of the Houses of Parliament.

95
00:10:39,942 --> 00:10:43,551
I mean, ours has become a sort of civilised fisticuff.

96
00:10:43,571 --> 00:10:48,743
But I mean, if you look at Syria, for instance, what's happening there, it's absolutely awful.

97
00:10:52,705 --> 00:11:00,370
And then this lovely question, you see that beings, like all of us, want to live without hate, want to live without harming and hostility and enmity.

98
00:11:00,412 --> 00:11:04,254
We want to live in peace, yet we live in hate.

99
00:11:05,895 --> 00:11:08,057
Harming each other, hostile and as enemies.

100
00:11:09,578 --> 00:11:11,860
So what's the cause of that?

101
00:11:14,383 --> 00:11:18,787
And in this particular passage, the Buddha points to envy and niggardliness.

102
00:11:19,187 --> 00:11:22,289
I love that word, niggardly.

103
00:11:22,759 --> 00:11:24,621
I think selfishness would have been probably.

104
00:11:25,403 --> 00:11:27,203
It's just envy and selfishness.

105
00:11:28,264 --> 00:11:29,486
Wanting what others have.

106
00:11:35,352 --> 00:11:37,355
And then we have this process, you see.

107
00:11:39,697 --> 00:11:41,999
What gives rise to liking and disliking?

108
00:11:42,779 --> 00:11:44,841
They arise from desire.

109
00:11:45,423 --> 00:11:46,943
What gives rise to desire?

110
00:11:47,565 --> 00:11:48,765
They arise from thinking.

111
00:11:49,466 --> 00:11:51,889
When the mind thinks about something, desire arises.

112
00:11:52,357 --> 00:11:54,960
When the mind thinks of nothing, desire does not arise.

113
00:11:56,000 --> 00:11:57,241
What gives rise to thinking?

114
00:11:58,062 --> 00:12:01,086
Thinking arises from elaborate perceptions and notions.

115
00:12:01,225 --> 00:12:04,729
So remember, this was our habits.

116
00:12:04,828 --> 00:12:11,554
It's a difficult word to translate, but it means everything that we can create through an act of will.

117
00:12:13,297 --> 00:12:17,200
And that translates into all our habits, emotional and thought habits.

118
00:12:19,581 --> 00:12:21,724
So you're sitting...

119
00:12:22,057 --> 00:12:51,677
you know just comfortably in a chair and suddenly out of the blue this desire arises to kill somebody so before you know it that's a thief from the local post office before you know it you're planning it you've got your mates and off you go of course it can happen on the positive side too you can imagine yourself saving the world and who knows what could happen then so it's a case of recognising the importance of catching our thoughts

120
00:12:52,432 --> 00:13:20,144
catch it right at the inception to actually know what's driving that thought and then to just let it pass and to stay with the with whatever negative state there is in the heart wait for it to pass you see then we have this whole business about causation about everything everything is dependent on something else

121
00:13:20,480 --> 00:13:27,749
So we can talk about a causality, some of it is dependent on things that have happened in the past, and then they keep producing things.

122
00:13:28,950 --> 00:13:32,815
So remember that dependent upon feeling, we had this craving, this desire.

123
00:13:35,337 --> 00:13:38,221
So we had, you know, like ice cream, you see.

124
00:13:38,240 --> 00:13:41,846
It brings up a nice feeling when you think of ice cream, at least for most people.

125
00:13:41,865 --> 00:13:43,847
So then you get a craving for it, a desire for it.

126
00:13:43,868 --> 00:13:47,111
Then there's that pursuit for it, see, wanting to get it.

127
00:13:47,833 --> 00:13:50,759
And with that pursuit there comes the decision making.

128
00:13:51,760 --> 00:13:54,725
What to do about it, what to do about how you're going to get it.

129
00:13:55,005 --> 00:13:58,913
Dependent on that, the desire grows.

130
00:13:59,072 --> 00:14:02,077
And dependent on that there comes the attachment, I really want it.

131
00:14:02,759 --> 00:14:06,365
And the possessiveness, keeping it, holding it.

132
00:14:07,187 --> 00:14:12,254
And dependent upon this possessiveness, this whole niggardliness comes up again.

133
00:14:13,804 --> 00:14:16,469
And depending upon niggardliness, there's defensiveness.

134
00:14:16,489 --> 00:14:17,791
You've got to protect what you have.

135
00:14:18,772 --> 00:14:23,239
And because of defensiveness, various evil, unwholesome things originate.

136
00:14:23,278 --> 00:14:30,809
The taking up of clubs and weapons, conflicts, quarrels and disputes, insults, slander and falsehood.

137
00:14:30,830 --> 00:14:42,326
So it's really also being aware of how things progress through certain stages and being able to stop the process right at the point where you can

138
00:14:42,711 --> 00:14:44,654
Which is the point of the arising of desire.

139
00:14:45,496 --> 00:14:46,599
That's where we have control.

140
00:14:46,999 --> 00:14:48,761
Once it grabs us, it's very difficult.

141
00:14:49,344 --> 00:14:51,626
Once it's really got some power behind it.

142
00:14:58,620 --> 00:15:01,945
And then we go back now to the roots of violence and oppression.

143
00:15:01,965 --> 00:15:06,373
And this comes down to these three roots of greed, hatred and delusions.

144
00:15:06,792 --> 00:15:14,018
So remember the delusion as we experience it is that we want to seek some sort of permanent happiness in the world.

145
00:15:14,138 --> 00:15:17,480
Even if it's not permanent happiness, we want to be constantly happy.

146
00:15:17,881 --> 00:15:21,284
And we tend to associate happiness with mental state of happiness.

147
00:15:22,566 --> 00:15:24,687
And so we're always driving towards that end.

148
00:15:25,327 --> 00:15:28,791
And because of that, there's a sense of holding on to it.

149
00:15:28,890 --> 00:15:30,211
You get your acquisitiveness.

150
00:15:31,553 --> 00:15:35,376
And then you've got to protect it and you get your aversion, your hatred.

151
00:15:35,417 --> 00:15:36,697
And if it's too big, you run from it.

152
00:15:37,471 --> 00:15:44,100
So it's really understanding that this goes very deep, it goes deep into our relationship to our lives.

153
00:15:51,589 --> 00:15:59,139
So whereas in the second section we were talking about how we cause suffering for ourselves, in the third one we talk about how we cause it for everybody else as well.

154
00:16:00,780 --> 00:16:03,764
Or at least how we're catalysts for other people's suffering.

155
00:16:05,197 --> 00:16:11,946
And then finally we had these wonderful images of a beginning that is undiscoverable.

156
00:16:15,691 --> 00:16:18,495
So we had the image of grass and sticks, you see.

157
00:16:23,041 --> 00:16:32,553
If you were to cut up whatever grass sticks and branches and foliage there are in this rose apple land, Jambudipa, that's India, and collect them all together in a single heap,

158
00:16:33,630 --> 00:16:37,817
And having done so, you'd have separated them saying, this is my mother, this is my mother's mother.

159
00:16:38,879 --> 00:16:42,043
The sequence of mothers and grandmothers would now come to an end.

160
00:16:43,485 --> 00:16:45,629
You'd be going back into endless time.

161
00:16:51,638 --> 00:16:54,061
And then there was the image of the balls of clay.

162
00:16:54,100 --> 00:17:00,650
If they reduced this great earth to balls of clay the size of jujube kernels, I presume they're very small.

163
00:17:01,511 --> 00:17:03,434
You say, this is my father, this is my father's father.

164
00:17:04,478 --> 00:17:05,598
And you'd never get to the end.

165
00:17:05,699 --> 00:17:11,365
Even though you got rid of all your jujube seed clay balls.

166
00:17:11,384 --> 00:17:16,310
You still wouldn't have come to the end of your search for your father's father's father's father.

167
00:17:18,833 --> 00:17:20,275
And then there was the image of the mountain.

168
00:17:21,276 --> 00:17:22,517
Made of solid rock.

169
00:17:22,596 --> 00:17:23,898
A massive solid rock.

170
00:17:25,160 --> 00:17:27,382
Seven miles long, seven miles wide and so on.

171
00:17:27,442 --> 00:17:28,804
Seven miles high.

172
00:17:28,824 --> 00:17:32,847
And every hundred years a man would stroke it once with a piece of fine cloth.

173
00:17:34,194 --> 00:17:36,558
How long it would take to wear the mountain down.

174
00:17:37,279 --> 00:17:39,603
What a horrible image is that?

175
00:17:40,023 --> 00:17:47,736
Then he gave us the image of the river Ganges.

176
00:17:47,915 --> 00:17:53,585
The grains of sand between the point where the river Ganges originates and the point where it enters the great ocean.

177
00:17:53,605 --> 00:17:54,767
It's not easy to count these.

178
00:17:55,949 --> 00:17:57,371
Hundreds and hundreds of thousands.

179
00:17:58,633 --> 00:17:59,493
He says these mountains

180
00:17:59,811 --> 00:18:10,724
It's not easy to count the eons, the hundreds of eons, the hundreds of thousands of eons that we've been roaming around in samsara, this onward going.

181
00:18:10,744 --> 00:18:13,228
And then finally, there was the dog on a leash.

182
00:18:15,711 --> 00:18:21,096
Tied to this pole, running round and round and round, helpless, unable to liberate himself.

183
00:18:21,557 --> 00:18:25,962
And that post, remember, going back to an early thing, is the sense of self.

184
00:18:26,683 --> 00:18:26,763
See?

185
00:18:28,718 --> 00:18:32,402
So here we've been looking at the darker side of life.

186
00:18:32,422 --> 00:18:35,785
The fact that how we cause suffering for ourselves.

187
00:18:36,925 --> 00:18:38,708
And what the root of that suffering is.

188
00:18:39,189 --> 00:18:43,432
And it always goes back to this essential problem about relationship.

189
00:18:44,713 --> 00:18:48,577
As to asking ourselves who we are or what we are.

190
00:18:49,199 --> 00:18:52,281
And what is our relationship to the life that we live.

191
00:18:52,301 --> 00:18:53,123
And remember that.

192
00:18:56,038 --> 00:19:01,766
It's recognizing that as something to really investigate.

193
00:19:02,547 --> 00:19:04,749
That liberates us from that wrong relationship.

194
00:19:07,112 --> 00:19:14,059
And the liberation of that wrong relationship is what the Buddha means by Nibbana.

195
00:19:14,440 --> 00:19:17,324
Nibbana has various meanings to it.

196
00:19:17,344 --> 00:19:19,006
One of them is no more desire.

197
00:19:19,846 --> 00:19:21,788
Now that's not wholesome desire.

198
00:19:22,068 --> 00:19:25,252
I mean the Buddha upon enlightenment had the desire to

199
00:19:25,721 --> 00:19:27,943
teach others what he'd come to understand.

200
00:19:28,744 --> 00:19:31,186
It's this desire which gets us into trouble.

201
00:19:33,628 --> 00:19:40,516
That's one of the core meanings that the commentaries give to this word Nibbana.

202
00:19:41,236 --> 00:19:42,877
No desire.

203
00:19:50,424 --> 00:19:51,065
So that's it.

204
00:19:51,306 --> 00:19:52,826
We have to go away glum.

205
00:19:53,329 --> 00:19:57,076
Think about our lives, is it?

206
00:19:57,277 --> 00:20:01,022
Try to get us out of our glumminess.

207
00:20:03,688 --> 00:20:08,476
I can only hope that all these lectures have been of some assistance.

208
00:20:08,496 --> 00:20:13,825
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

209
00:20:13,845 --> 00:20:18,814
Salud, salut, salut.

